title: March Time Trials
description: Two full months of time trial data!
contents:
Contents Nitro Tracks Retro Tracks Bonus Tracks Day of Month Time of Day My first post on this blog looked at my Mario Kart time trial data for February 2022, the first month I began tracking this data. I’ve been practicing time trials on-and-off for a few years, so I didn’t expect any major time saves. In that post, most of the line graphs are flat because I was only improving my times by a handful of milliseconds. In contrast, when the new tracks were released I immediately saw major time saves as I learned the tracks. But I’ve been interested in seeing how the graphs look over a longer period of time. I’ve been playing more regularly than ever before, and recently I’ve been changing up my build to improve my speed. I’m expecting to see larger time saves than in February. This post reviews all my personal bests for MK8DX tracks in February and March, grouped by release group (nitro, retro, and bonus) and cup. I excluded the new tracks because this data is covered more extensively in the post linked above. The new tracks were released on March 17th and I played nonstop the following week. The spike on March 12th is when I switched my kart from the City Tripper to the Biddybuggy. Time of Day I wanted to see what time of day I set the most PBs and compare it to February. I began a new job in April and I tried to adjust my schedule to be less nocturnal during March. Trying out a new graph so apologies if this format is awkward. The left side is February and March is on the right. Changes in my sleep schedule are reflected in the graph. In March I mostly PB’d before midnight and I played in the middle of the day, a time in February I would typically be asleep. Is this a decent, roundabout way of tracking my sleep schedule? Idk. But it was fun to change up the data visualization from my normal bar/line graphs.

title: New Tracks!
description: My time trial and speedrun data for the new DLC tracks.
contents:
Contents Intro Time Trials 150cc 200cc Speedrun Intro Eight new Mario Kart tracks were released on March 18th, part of the first wave of DLC to come out over the next two years. The two new cups, Golden Dash and Lucky Cat, include amazing tracks such as Coconut Mall and Ninja Hideaway, and some less stellar tracks like Toad’s Circuit and Choco Mountain. Since the new tracks were released, I have grinding them in time trials and successfully completed two speedruns. Time Trials Time trials are the easiest way to learn and practice the new maps, especially before they were available in online play. There were stark drops in my times as I learned and improved at the maps. Sharp drops typically indicate when I discovered a new shortcut that significantly saved time. Ninja Hideaway showed the most improvement, with approximately 15 seconds saved between my first and most recent PB. As the month went on, it became harder to improve my times and set new PBs. However, some tracks I practice far less than others because they’re not as fun (see: Tokyo Blur, Toad Circuit, and Sky Garden). Overall, my favorite tracks have been Ninja Hideaway, Coconut Mall, and Paris Promenade. I think the shortcuts on these tracks make them particularly fun. My favorite shortcut in all of the new tracks is in Coconut Mall, shown in the clip below. While most people know the shortcut through the shop, I’ve seen little mention of the extension of the shortcut. I wasn’t able to actually save time on it and because the path is so narrow I still often run into the railing trying to complete it. Still, it is very satisfying when I’m able to nail it correctly. 200cc Since online play randomly selects some courses to be played at 200cc, I’ve been trying to incorporate it into my practice more often. title: Clint Stevens Mario Kart extended universe
description: Clint plays the new tracks with chat.
contents:
Contents Intro Clint’s stream Tracks Played Players Placement Frequency Average Results Rankings swushwoi’s stream Overall Clint’s Best/Worst Tracks Player Rankings Final Words Intro Per my previous posts, I’ve been tracking data on who plays in Clint Steven’s online Mario Kart games and how they place. This post mostly shows data from games played on March 18th/19th, the day new tracks were released. Clint typically plays online in worldwide mode, usually joining a full lobby and requiring snipers to wait for a spot to open. Once in, there is no limit to how many games a person can play. This day, Clint created a room to play with people on his friends list, and he reset the room after eight games, allowing more people the chance to join. Unfortunately I wasn’t able to join a room on release day. However, another streamer, swushwoi, played later that day and many of the players in her lobby overlapped with Clint’s. They were kind enough to let me play so I got my MK fix and I collected results from her games as well.1 At the bottom of the post you can find Clint’s best and worst tracks and the overall player rankings for 2022. Feel free to use the table of contents to quickly jump around. Clint’s stream On March 18th, Clint played 40 games with chat. Creating a private room allowed the options for team games and 200cc Grand Prix. There were 16 games played with teams, 24 without; 16 games were 150cc, 8 were 150cc mirrored, and 16 were 200cc. Snurglez and plop also had great nights, averaging in the S-tier. The most improved player was Dylan, who ranked as D+ in the previous rankings I tallied. On March 19th, Dylan averaged an A rank, bringing his overall rank up to a C. Clint’s overall rank continues to be a B+, though his average slightly improved from 5.8 to 5.67. swushwoi’s stream As I mentioned in the intro, I was not able to play in Clint’s games but I joined the lobby of another streamer, swushwoi, who was playing with other people who regularly play with Clint. There were 12 players in swushwoi’s stream, three of whom played with Clint earlier in the night: swushwoi, zipcola, and FruitYoshi. Additionally, myself and mooney have played with Clint before but not that night. In swushwoi’s stream, 41 races were played, 24 on teams and 17 without. I’m not quite sure how to do this but if you have any ideas feel free to whisper me on Twitch. Final Words Collecting this Mario Kart data has been a fun project for the past month. I hope others find it as interesting as I do. I initially collected data for just Clint and myself, but it didn’t feel right to leave out the rest of the community, even though it took some extra time to gather everyone’s data. I love that I’ve been able to document a community of people coming together to play some games. I’ll be starting a full time job the day after creating this post. I’m not sure how often I’ll be able to keep playing in games or keep up with the data. However, all of the data I’ve collected I’ve made public on GitHub, so in the event I’m not able to continue this and someone else wishes to, please feel free to use what I’ve already collected.2 You can also check the RMarkdown files to see how I used it (sorry it’s a bit of a mess). Love you all, Sarah Thus begins the Clint Stevens Mario Kart extended universe↩︎ Note: This post was the first one I began collecting data on whether courses were mirrored.↩︎

Five times during the stream, Clint was kicked out of the lobby before the race finished. Snipers scrambled into the new lobbies, but sometimes it took a few games for spots to open. The results of one game were also affected by connection issues. During the 48th race, Royal Raceway, I saw Clint pass me in a bullet bill shortly before the finish line. His result originally showed a 6th place finish, but after a long moment of lag his result changed to 8th. However, this is not what I saw during my recording. Notice that not only are the results different for those in 5th-11th, but so are the Elo rankings. So I looked back to the Elo rankings for the next race, to see who’s screen showed the true results. The Elo rankings for the next race matched my results on both of our screens, so I used those for the dataset. The results are: 5th–Moonmoon (BatChest), 6th–Clint, 7th–Sarah, 8th–gamergirl, 9th–kaleighboo, 10th–Jim, and 11th–Dylan. In that stream I never placed above 5th; tonight I had 5 top-3 results. I’m also the only sniper to have placed at least once in every result. Highlights There were multiple moments during my last stream sniper where I wish I had recorded my POV and reaction. I don’t think my internet could currently handle stream sniping (nor am I sure I want to), so I just recorded it locally. For the record, I forgot to adjust my settings to record at a higher quality, and I’m still figuring out picture-in-picture layouts and when to cut. Guilty Only Clint and Moonmoon were ahead of me going into the final turn of the first lap of Ice Ice Outpost. I missed the mushroom skip, but Moonmoon ran into the wall and Clint went far left. I decided to use my sound box before the finish line to give myself a solid first into the second lap. I knew I tapped him, but I didn’t realize he’d been hurtled over the side until I caught the replay on his stream. Play of the Game Cloudtop Cruise is usually one of my least favorite maps, but yesterday I nailed the mirrored version. Halfway through the second lap, Clint was in first and I was in second. A blue shell nailed him just before the jump into the cloud tunnel. I stayed far to the right, avoiding the blast radius, and I zoomed far into first. On the final lap I was blue shelled in nearly the same spot, allowing the pack to catch up with me. In the final stretch, Dylan’s bullet bill pushed him ahead of Clint and then myself. Just before risking the final shortcut, Dylan threw away his entire defense. I let go of my red shell and the timing was perfect, causing Dylan to fall halfway through the jump. I finished third, Clint finished fourth. Sorry Dylan. Speedrunning PB [1:58:38] After some solid online play, I wasn’t ready to put away Mario Kart for the day just yet. I decided to start a speedrun around 5AM and it began horrendously. However, massive time saves on Ice Ice Outpost and Animal Crossing saved me huge time. You can watch the speedrun here. Future time saves Thwomp Ruins: ran into pillar at end of water section on 2nd lap Toad Harbor: 1st lap - ran into wall at end of awning section; 2nd lap - hit every barrel under awning Twisted Mansion: tapped into hammer on 2nd lap Mount Wario: Ran into boulder in cave section Bone Dry Dunes: Got chomped on first lap Rainbow Road: Fall in first turn Cheep Cheep Beach: ran into wall at end of beach section on final lap Toad’s Turnpike: ran into railing a lot Dry Dry Dunes: very low on coins entire race Donut Plains 3: gopher run in Royal Raceway: ran off in final turn section Wario Stadium & Dragon Driftway: AI ran me into wall at v beginning Sherbet Land: trouble with columns in underwater section Music Park: made the shortcut but v messy Piranha Plant Slide: ran into goomba Neo Bowser City: fell on tricky turn final lap Ribbon Road: fell on 2nd ramp first lap

title: Biddybuggy or bust
contents:
Contents Overview The Run Future time saves Online Play Overview For years1 I have stuck with the same Mario Kart build: Isabelle, City Tripper, Leaf Tires, and Paper Glider. I know it’s a sub-optimal build, but I wanted to max out my abilities with that cart before switching to a meta build. Isabelle jazzed on the City Tripper. Yesterday I decided to make the switch. It was not the first day I tried the Biddybuggy–that was Valentine’s Day (where I set 16 PBs in one day). I tried speedrunning that night, but I was struggling with turns on the new build and had a lot of falls, so I cut the run short. I switched back to the City Tripper and didn’t think much of it. Then my speedrun times began to level out and I embarrassed myself in online play, so I was ready to give the Biddybuggy another shot. Folding to the meta.First I extensively practiced the time trials, and was setting PB after PB. I began getting a grasp of the biddybuggy handling. I knew if I tried the 48 track speedrun, I would set a fat personal best. Around 11 PM I tried to stream the run on Twitch, but my internet was having issues and I was getting a lot of dropped frames.2 For the first time I decided to just record the speedrun locally and upload it to YouTube. Once I started running, it quickly became obvious that my predictions were right. I had saved over half a minute before getting to the halfway point. The second half of the race had a handful of falls (future time saves) and I accidentally rigged the game to play the Animal Crossing winter track (notorious for horrible traction and adding excessive time). Still, I managed to easily PB by 48 seconds, an insane time save considering how many falls I had. {"x":{"data":[{"x":[1,2,3,4,5,6],"y":[7266,7222,7205,7190,7219,7142],"text":["attempt: 1

My reaction during the run was almost upset. Of course I was happy to PB, but I was frustrated for two reasons: 1. Why are two carts (Biddybuggy and Wiggler) sooo much better than other carts? 2. Why did I resist playing the meta for so long?3 Biddybuggy and Wiggler are basically the only two carts in the game.Time after time there were sections where I normally would’ve run into a wall or object, but the Biddybuggy allowed me to safely navigate around obstacles. During Dry Dry Desert I decided to risk going underneath a Poke to grab a coin, an unnecessary risk. After successfully grabbing it, I said aloud, “This cart is just giving me a confidence I didn’t know I was missing.” The Run After the run, I submitted my time to speedrun.com. At the time of writing this, I moved from 206th to 180th, an improvement of 26 spots. You can watch the full speedrun below. Disclaimer: I’d been awake for about 26-27 hours when I began the run. Be warned that since it was just me, I didn’t talk much and I mumbled a lot. While the recorded video contains gameplay audio, I was listening to my own music during the run. If I seem like I’m talking to myself, I was mouthing along song lyrics. When I did talk, I was often cursing out my gameplay or wondering why certain songs weren’t playing (problems with soundcloud). Future time saves There are a handful of major time saves still available: Neo Bowser City: one fall (SNES) Rainbow Road: one fall on shortcut on second lap Ice Ice Outpost: 3 falls - first lap landed too far right off first ramp, first and third lap final ramp cut in too late Ribbon Road: 2 falls - missed second ramp on first and second lap Animal Crossing: accidentally rigged for winter track And some more minor time saves: Donut Plains 3: botched shortcut Super Bell Subway: ran into subway on second lap Toad’s Turnpike: ran into bus on 3rd lap Music Park: botched final shortcut Cheeseland: twice went slightly off road near second chomp chomp, hit a wall Bone-Dry Dunes: ran into wall one turn Online Play Today I practiced online with the biddybuggy. The room I was placed in was pretty well balanced, with nearly everyone’s rating being between 7500-9000. The average rating going into the final game was 7882. I kept track of my results, and I’m content with how I placed. I landed in the top three 9 times (36%) and my lowest placement was 9th. My average result was 4.88. My rating at the end of the night was 7702. I use “years” loosely because I didn’t play much from late 2018 till the beginning of this year. Grad school got in the way of Mario Kart.↩︎ I’m currently on my neighbor’s internet and I’ll have my own installed on March 28th, so that should cut down on streaming problems.↩︎ Answer: I thought the City Tripper was cute and I liked committing to the bit of full Animal Crossing build.↩︎

title: March 8th Stream Snipe
description: Stream sniping Clint Stevens in Mario Kart.
contents:
Contents Intro Analysis All Races Map Frequency Best/Worst Tracks Play of the Game Review & Goals Intro A few weeks ago I sent Clint Stevens a friend request on the Switch with little expectation it would go anywhere. But I lucked out on Tuesday and got added. dang I should finish the third game I knew my online game was rusty—most of my ~7K Elo ranking was from spring 2018 or earlier (four years ago wtf). I picked the game back up recently but I’ve been doing no-item speedruns, which is good for practicing the maps and shortcuts but terrible for item management. After the game I made a spreadsheet of which games I played in and the results for myself and Clint. I’d like to add other members of chat, but it’s a bit tedious to go through the VOD and manually enter everyone’s results.1 Analysis All Races In total, I was able to play in 39 races with Clint and the other members of chat, excluding two games where Clint left but myself and other snipers continued to play. The below graph shows how Clint and I placed in every race. The graph is interactive, so feel free to hover over any point to see more details. <\/th>\n racer<\/th>\n track<\/th>\n avg<\/th>\n plays<\/th>\n <\/tr>\n <\/thead>\n<\/table>","options":{"autoWidth":false,"columnDefs":[{"className":"dt-right","targets":[3,4]},{"orderable":false,"targets":0}],"order":[],"orderClasses":false,"orderCellsTop":true}},"evals":[],"jsHooks":[]} Clint’s best tracks were Wild Woods, Electrodrome, and Wario’s Gold Mine. His worst tracks were Mute City, Yoshi Circuit, and Sunshine Airport. My top tracks were Moo Moo Meadows and Royal Raceway. My worst tracks were Wild Woods, Donut Plains, and Animal Crossing (ironic considering my build). Note that these best/worst rankings are subject to change as more games are played. Play of the Game My favorite play was in the 30th race, just after the first lap of Cheep Cheep Beach. Clint was in first and I was in second. I noticed him slowing down and I saw the blue shell approaching just as I passed him. I said “oh hell no” and came to a stop so he was back in first and got hit. After reviewing the tape, the blue shell looks to be circling Clint before I slowed down, so I probably would’ve been safe if I continued on. (I also was too close and still got hit by the shell). Still, it was worth it for the laughs. Review & Goals I suck compared to the other racers. It’s hard to deny with the graphs in my face. But that’s okay, I know I can get better. The main reasons I suck at the moment are: 1. Very little online experience the past four years. Despite knowing the maps well and confidently taking shortcuts, I am out of practice with items. Item lines are different than speedrunning lines. Too often I would miss items because I hugged a corner too close or I wasn’t paying attention to the item being taken by the racer in front of me. Items are essential to good online play, so I really need to practice using them. It’s also important to know when to use them; too often I would play overly defensive and not let go of items when I was far back in the pack. 2. I never practice 200cc. I did not know how to brake drift and I routinely ran into walls or fell off the map. 3. I play a non-meta build of full Animal Crossing: Isabelle, City Tripper, Leaf Tires, and Paper Glider. I’ve already begun taking steps to improve. I watched some YouTube videos on item management and played for a few hours online Wednesday. I routinuely came in first, but I’m being placed in rooms significantly less competitive. But my Elo is rapidly increasing, so hopefully I’ll start getting tougher rooms. I also watched some videos on brake drifting and I’ve been going through the 200cc grand prix (which I’m surprised I never did before). I still don’t enjoy 200cc, but I’m running into walls less often. But I refuse to change my build. (update: JK I changed it two days later) If anyone else wants to help collect this data, please let me know! (update: JK I did it the next day)↩︎
